* Group-IV, III-V and II-VI Semiconductors", John Wiley & Sons, 
* Ltd, 2009.
* [07Ada] S. Adachi, "Lattice thermal conductivity of group-IV 
* and III-V semiconductor alloys", J. Appl. Phys., vol. 102, pp. 
* 063502, 2007.
* [59Abr] M. S. Abrahams, R. Braunstein, F. D. Rosi, "Thermal, 
* electrical and optical properties of (In,Ga)As alloys", J. 
* Phys. chem. Solids, vol. 10, pp. 204, 1959.
* [90Ara] D. G. Arasly, R. N. Ragimov, M. I. Aliev, 
* "Characteristics of phonon scattering in GaxIn1-xAs solid 
* solutions", Sov. Phys. Semicond., vol. 24, pp. 225, 1990.
* [01Vur] I. Vurgaftman, J. R. Meyer, L. R. Ram-Mohan, "Band 
* parameters for III-V compound semiconductors and their alloys", 
* J. Appl. Phys., vol. 89, no. 11, pp. 5815, 2001.
* [90Jai] S. C. Jain, J. M. McGregor, D. J. Roulston, "Band-gap 
* narrowing in novel III-V semiconductors", J. Appl. Phys., vol. 
* 68, no. 7, pp. 3747, 1990.
* [78Sem] N. A. Semikolenova, I. M. Nesmelova, E. N. Khabarov, 
* "Investigation of the impurity interaction mechanism in indium 
* arsenide", Sov. Phys. Semicond., vol. 12, no. 10, pp. 1139, 
* 1978.
* [90Yao] H. Yao, A. Compaan, "Plasmons, photoluminescence, and 
* band-gap narrowing in very heavily doped n-GaAs", Appl. Phys. 
* Lett., vol. 57, no. 2, pp. 147, 1990.
* [89Bor] C. Borghs et al., "Band-gap narrowing in highly doped 
* n- and p-type GaAs studied by photoluminescence spectroscopy", 
* J. Appl. Phys., vol. 66, no. 9, pp. 4381, 1989.
* [80Ala] K. Alavi, R. L. Aggarwal, S. H. Groves, "Interband 
* magnetoabsorption of In0.535Ga0.47As", Phys. Rev. B, vol. 21, 
* no. 3, pp. 1311, 1980.
* [00Sot] M. Sotoodeh, A. H. Khalid, A. A. Rezazadeh, "Empirical 
* low-field mobility model for III-V compounds applicable in 
* device simulation codes", J. Appl. Phys., vol. 87, no. 6, pp. 
* 2890, 2000.
* [Ioffe] http://www.ioffe.ru/SVA/NSM/Semicond/
* [85Osa] F. Osaka, T. Mikawa, T. Kaneda, "Impact ionization 
* coefficients of electrons and holes in (100)-oriented Ga1-
* xInxAsyP1-y," IEEE J. Quantum Electron., vol. QE-21, pp. 1326-
* 1338, 1985.


Epsilon
{ 
  * Ratio of the permittivities of material and vacuum
  * epsilon() = epsilon

  * Interpolation from InGaAs.par
	epsilon	= 13.642	# [1] # [05Ada]
}

LatticeHeatCapacity
{ 
  * lumped electron-hole-lattice heat capacity
  * cv() = cv + cv_b * T + cv_c * T^2 + cv_d * T^3 

  * Interpolation from InGaAs.par   
	cv		= 1.8724	# [J/(Kcm^3)] # [1] # [09Ada]
	cv_b		= 0.0000e+00	# [J/(K^2*cm^3)]
	cv_c		= 0.0000e+00	# [J/(K^3*cm^3)]
	cv_d		= 0.0000e+00	# [J/(K^4*cm^3)]
}

Kappa
{ 
  * Lattice thermal conductivity
  * Formula = 0:
  * kappa() = 1 / ( 1/kappa + 1/kappa_b * T + 1/kappa_c * T^2 )

	Formula = 0

  * Interpolation from InGaAs.par
	# mole-fraction dependence from [59Abr], [90Ara] and [07Ada]
	1/kappa  = 20.1933
	1/kappa_b  = 0.0
	1/kappa_c  = 0.0	
}

Kappa_aniso
{ 
  * Lattice thermal conductivity
  * Formula = 0:
  * kappa() = 1 / ( 1/kappa + 1/kappa_b * T + 1/kappa_c * T^2 )

	Formula = 0

  * Interpolation from InGaAs.par
	# mole-fraction dependence from [59Abr], [90Ara] and [07Ada]
	1/kappa  = 20.1933
	1/kappa_b  = 0.0
	1/kappa_c  = 0.0	
}

Bandgap
{
  * Eg = Eg0 + alpha Tpar^2 / (beta + Tpar) - alpha T^2 / (beta + T)
  * Parameter 'Tpar' specifies the value of lattice 
  * temperature, at which parameters below are defined
  * Chi0 is electron affinity.

  * Interpolation from InGaAs.par
	Tpar = 0 # [K]
	Eg0	= 0.8161	# [eV] # [01Vur] 
	alpha	= 4.0032e-04	# [eV/K] # [01Vur] 
	beta	= 1.4517e+02	# [K] # [01Vur] 
	Chi0	= 4.5918		# [eV] # [05Ada]
	EgMin	= 1.5000e-01	# [eV]
}

JainRoulston
{
  * deltaEg = A_i N^(1/3) + B_i N^(1/4) + C_i N^(1/2) + D_i N^(1/2)
  * where i is n for n-type or p for p-type

	A_n	= 3.0390e-08	# [eV cm] # Interpolation from fitted value based on [78Sem, 90Yao, 89Bor]
	B_n	= 3.1150e-07	# [eV cm^(3/4)] # Interpolation from fitted value based on [78Sem, 90Yao, 89Bor]
	C_n	= 3.3043e-12	# [eV cm^(3/2)] # Interpolation from fitted value based on [78Sem, 90Yao, 89Bor]
	D_n	= 3.4260e-11	# [eV cm^(3/2)] # Interpolation from fitted value based on [78Sem, 90Yao, 89Bor]

	A_p	= 9.2783e-09	# [eV cm] # Interpolation from fitted value based on [90Jai]
	B_p	= 3.8100e-07	# [eV cm^(3/4)] # Interpolation from fitted value based on [90Jai]
	C_p	= 3.0156e-12	# [eV cm^(3/2)] # Interpolation from fitted value based on [90Jai]
	D_p	= 2.3280e-13	# [eV cm^(3/2)] # Interpolation from fitted value based on [90Jai]
}

FreeCarrierAbsorption
{
  * Coefficients for free carrier absorption:
  * fcaalpha_n for electrons,
  * fcaalpha_p for holes

  * FCA = (alpha_n * n + alpha_p * p) * Light Intensity
	fcaalpha_n   = 4.0000e-18    # [cm^2]
	fcaalpha_p   = 8.0000e-18    # [cm^2]
}

BandstructureParameters
{
  * Parameters for k.p bandstructure calculation:

  * Zincblende crystals:
  * Luttinger parameters gamma_1, gamma_2, gamma_3
  * Spin-orbit split-off energy so
  * Matrix element parameters for TE and TM modes ep_te and ep_tm

  * Wurtzite crystals:
  * Effective mass parameters A1, A2, A3, A4, A5, A6
  * Spin-orbit split-off energy so
  * Crystal-field split  energy cr
  * Matrix element parameters for TE and TM modes ep_te and ep_tm
  *
  *
  * Interpolation from InGaAs.par
	gamma_1      = 14.0315  # [1]
	gamma_2      = 5.386   # [1]
	gamma_3      = 6.186   # [1]
	so   = 0.3612  # [eV]
	ep_te        = 24.931  # [eV]
	ep_tm        = 24.931  # [eV]
	A1   = 0.0000e+00    # [1]
	A2   = 0.0000e+00    # [1]
	A3   = 0.0000e+00    # [1]
	A4   = 0.0000e+00    # [1]
	A5   = 0.0000e+00    # [1]
	A6   = 0.0000e+00    # [1]
	cr   = 0.0000e+00    # [eV]
}

QWStrain
{
  * Zincblende crystals:
  *   Parameters: a_nu, a_c, b, C_12, C_11
  *   StrainConstant eps (formula = 1) or lattice constant
  *   a0 (formula = 2) for energy shift of quantum-well
  *   subbands.
  *   a0(T) = a0 + alpha (T-Tpar)

  * Wurtzite crystals:
  *   Parameters: a_c, D1, D2, D3, D4, C_13, C_33
  *   Lattice constants a0 and c0 (formula 2 must be used)
  *   a0(T) = a0 + alpha (T-Tpar)
  *   c0(T) = c0 + alpha (T-Tpar)

  * Default formula     = 1     # [1]

  * Interpolation from InGaAs.par
	a_nu 		= 1.0752    # [eV]
	a_c  		= -6.0623e+00   # [eV]
	b_shear	= -1.7530e+00   # [eV]
	C_11 		= 9.9975 # [1e-2 GPa]
	C_12 		= 4.9255 # [1e-2 GPa]
	eps  		= 0.0000e+00    # [1]
	a0   		= 5.8680e-10    # [m]
	alpha		= 3.2758e-15    # [m/K]
	D1		= 0.0000e+00    # [eV]
	D2		= 0.0000e+00    # [eV]
	D3		= 0.0000e+00    # [eV]
	D4		= 0.0000e+00    # [eV]
	C_13		= 0.0000e+00    # [1e-2 GPa]
	C_33		= 0.0000e+00    # [1e-2 GPa]
	c0		= 0.0000e+00    # [cm]
}

eDOSMass
{
	Formula = 2
  * me/m0 = (Nc300/2.540e19)^2/3
  * Nc(T) = Nc300 * (T/300)^3/2

  # Reference from [09Ada]
  * Interpolation from InGaAs.par
	Nc300 = 2.3327e+17		#[cm-3]
}

hDOSMass
{
	Formula = 2
  * mh/m0 = (Nv300/2.540e19)^2/3
  * Nv(T) = Nv300 * (T/300)^3/2

  # References from [01Vur] and [80Ala]
  * Interpolation from InGaAs.par
	Nv300 = 1.0886e+19		#[cm-3] 
} 

SchroedingerParameters:
{ 
  * For the hole masses for Schroedinger equation you can
  * use different formulas.
  * 0: use the isotropic density of states effective mass
  * 1: (for materials with Si-like hole band structure)
  *    m(k)/m0=1/(A+-sqrt(B+C*((xy)^2+(yz)^2+(zx)^2)))
  *    where k=(x,y,z) is unit normal vector in reziprocal
  *    space.  '+' for light hole band, '-' for heavy hole band
  * 2: Heavy hole mass mh and light hole mass ml are
  *    specified explicitly.
  *    Use me as electron mass for free-carrier effect in
  *    the refractive index model.
  * For electron masses, the following formula options exist:
  * 0: use the isotropic density of states effective mass
  * 1: (for materials with Si-like hole band structure)
  *    use the a, ml, and mm parameters from eDOSMass.
  *    Typically, this leads to anisotropy.
        formula = 0 ,   2       # [1]
  * Lifting of degeneracy of bulk valleys. The value for
  * electrons is added to the band edge for the subband
  * ladder of lower degeneracy if positive, and subtracted
  * from the band edge for the ladder of higher degeneracy
  * if negative. (that is, the value of the band edge is
  * always increased).  For holes, the value is subtracted from
  * the band edge for the heavy hole band is positive,
  * add added tp that of the light hole band if
  * negative.  The signs are such that the shift always
  * moves the band edges 'outward', away from midgap.  The
  * gap itself is defined as the separation of the
  * unshifted band edges and remains unaffected.
        offset  = 0.0000e+00 ,  0.0000e+00      # [eV]
  * Alternative to the specification of formula, offset,
  * and masses, you can make an arbitrary number of ladder
  * specification, 'eLadder(mz, mxy, deg, dE) and hLadder(...)
  * Here, mz is the quantization mass, mxy an in-plane DOS mass,
  * deg the ladder degeneracy, and dE an shift of the band edge
  * for the ladder (non-negative; the shift is always outward,
  * away from midgap).  When present, we solve the Schroedinger
  * equation separately for each ladder

  * Temperatures in rescaling of the mxy for eLadder and hLadder
        ShiftTemperature        = 1.0000e+10 ,  1.0000e+10      # [K]

  * Interpolation from InGaAs.par
        A    = 4.22  # [1]
        B    = 0.6084        # [1]
        C    = 23.058        # [1]
        ml   = 0.0475 # [1]
        mh   = 0.5087  # [1]
        me   = 0.0000e+00    # [1]
        eoffset      = 0.0000e+00    # [eV]
        hoffset      = 0.0000e+00    # [eV]
}

